content.description: A thinker!  Protection in the first 10 feet after the approach ramp is tricky.  Beyond this, options open up and the climbing improves rapidly.  Finish off with a jam-jug-mantle to chains!
content.protection: Small gear down low, with a #2 or #3 at the top.  Black alien or equivalent is helpful for the start.  An attentive belayer/spotter may be beneficial.
content.location: On the right hand side of a flat-topped pillar.  Shares the same top out with Rose Crack (to the left of this route).

content.description: An interesting but short route.  Start with a heel-toe plus stem, arm bar plus stem, fists plus stem, hand jams plus stem, and then finally a top-out.
content.protection:
1 of each (in this order):

#5

#4

#3

#2

And that's sewing it up.  If you really wanted you could squeeze in a #1 at the very top.

Chains at the top.
content.location: Left hand side of a pillar.  In the Bingham book, it is not listed and is to the left of "5.8 Corner."  Labeled in the Calderone book.

content.description:
This is a fun dihedral marred by rose bushes about a third of the way up the route. Climb up a ramp with a useful hand crack to the left, pull over to the right to a stance where rose bushes await you, fight your way past them, and enjoy a slowly widening hand-crack to the top.

(The route name was obtained from Dave Bingham's guide to the park.)
content.protection: Standard rack to #3 Camalot. Bolted rappel anchor at the top.
content.location: This route shares the same pillar as Unnamed 10d. It's the corner to the left of that route and has its own anchor.
